[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] In telecommunications, **provisioning** involves the process of preparing and equipping a network to allow it to provide new services to its users.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] In National Security/Emergency Preparedness telecommunications services, *"provisioning"* equates to *"initiation"* and includes altering the state of an existing priority service or capability.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] The concept of **network provisioning** or **service mediation**, mostly used in the telecommunication industry, refers to the provisioning of the customer's services to the network elements, which are various equipment connected in that network communication system.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Generally in telephony provisioning this is accomplished with network management database table mappings.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] It requires the existence of networking equipment and depends on network planning and design.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] In a modern signal infrastructure employing information technology (IT) at all levels, there is no possible distinction between telecommunications services and "higher level" infrastructure.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Accordingly, provisioning configures any required systems, provides users with access to data and technology resources, and refers to all enterprise-level information-resource management involved.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] As its core, the provisioning process monitors access rights and privileges to ensure the security of an enterprise's resources and user privacy.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] As a secondary responsibility, it ensures compliance and minimizes the vulnerability of systems to penetration and abuse.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] As a tertiary responsibility, it tries to reduce the amount of custom configuration using boot image control and other methods that radically reduce the number of different configurations involved.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Discussion of provisioning often appears in the context of virtualization, orchestration, utility computing, cloud computing, and open-configuration concepts and projects.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Once provisioning has taken place, the process of SysOpping ensures the maintenance of services to the expected standards.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Provisioning thus refers only to the setup or startup part of the service operation, and SysOpping to the ongoing support.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] The services which are assigned to the customer in the customer relationship management (CRM) have to be provisioned on the network element which is enabling the service and allows the customer to actually use the service.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] The relation between a service configured in the CRM and a service on the network elements is not necessarily a one-to-one relationship; for example, services like Microsoft Media Server (mms://) can be enabled by more than one network element.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] During the provisioning, the service mediation device translates the service and the corresponding parameters of the service to one or more services/parameters on the network elements involved.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] The algorithm used to translate a system service into network services is called **provisioning logic**.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Electronic invoice feeds from your carriers can be automatically downloaded directly into the core of the telecom expense management (TEM) software and it will immediately conduct an audit of each single line item charge all the way down to the User Support and Operations Center (USOC) level.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] The provisioning software will capture each circuit number provided by all of your carriers and if billing occurs outside of the contracted rate an exception rule will trigger a red flag and notify the pre-established staff member to review the billing error.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Server provisioning is a set of actions to prepare a server with appropriate systems, data and software, and make it ready for network operation.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] By auditing the system, you ensure OVAL compliance with limit vulnerability, ensure compliance, or install patches.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] After these actions, you restart the system and load the new software.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] This makes the system ready for operation.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Typically an internet service provider (ISP) or network operations center will perform these tasks to a well-defined set of parameters, for example, a boot image that the organization has approved and which uses software it has license to.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Many instances of such a boot image create a virtual dedicated host.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] There are many software products available to automate the provisioning of servers, services and end-user devices.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Examples: BMC Bladelogic Server Automation, HP Server Automation, IBM Tivoli Provisioning Manager, Redhat Kickstart, xCAT, HP Insight CMU, etc.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Middleware and applications can be installed either when the operating system is installed or afterwards by using an Application Service Automation tool.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Further questions are addressed in academia such as when provisioning should be issued and how many servers are needed in multi-tier, or multi-service applications.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] In cloud computing, servers may be provisioned via a web user interface or an application programming interface (API).
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] One of the unique things about cloud computing is how rapidly and easily this can be done.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Monitoring software can be used to trigger automatic provisioning when existing resources become too heavily stressed.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] In short, server provisioning configures servers based on resource requirements.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] The use of a hardware or software component (e.g. single/dual processor, RAM, HDD, RAID Controller, a number of LAN cards, applications, OS, etc.) depends on the functionality of the server, such as ISP, virtualization, NOS, or voice processing.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Server redundancy depends on the availability of servers in the organization.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Critical applications have less downtime when using cluster servers, RAID, or a mirroring system.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Service used by most larger-scale centers in part to avoid this.
