[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] There are several software on the market for server provisioning such as Cobbler or HP Intelligent Provisioning.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] User provisioning refers to the creation, maintenance and deactivation of user objects and user attributes, as they exist in one or more systems, directories or applications, in response to automated or interactive business processes.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] User provisioning software may include one or more of the following processes: change propagation, self-service workflow, consolidated user administration, delegated user administration, and federated change control.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] User objects may represent employees, contractors, vendors, partners, customers or other recipients of a service.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Services may include electronic mail, inclusion in a published user directory, access to a database, access to a network or mainframe, etc.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] User provisioning is a type of identity management software, particularly useful within organizations, where users may be represented by multiple objects on multiple systems and multiple instances.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] On-demand self-service is described by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) as an essential characteristic of cloud computing.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] The self-service nature of cloud computing lets end users obtain and remove cloud services―including applications, the infrastructure supporting the applications, and configuration― themselves without requiring the assistance of an IT staff member.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] The automatic self-servicing may target different application goals and constraints (e.g. deadlines and cost), as well as handling different application architectures (e.g., bags-of-tasks and workflows).
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Cloud users can obtain cloud services through a cloud service catalog or a self-service portal.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] Because business users can obtain and configure cloud services themselves, this means IT staff can be more productive and gives them more time to manage cloud infrastructures.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] One downside of cloud service provisioning is that it is not instantaneous.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] A cloud virtual machine (VM) can be acquired at any time by the user, but it may take up to several minutes for the acquired VM to be ready to use.
[src:pulumi/provisioning-technology] The VM startup time is dependent on factors, such as image size, VM type, data center location, and number of VMs.
